    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2914229273" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2914229273" />
    <a title="Elizabeth" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2105748-elizabeth"><img alt="Elizabeth" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1298394819p2/2105748.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2914229273?book_show_action=true">Jul 28, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elizabeth" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elizabeth" href="/user/show/2105748-elizabeth">Elizabeth</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/9801172-stones-for-ibarra">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2105748-elizabeth?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2914229273" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12362389803994062419">This book was sumptuous—the writing spare but rich with imagery and depth of scene, culture, and characters. I was reminded of Gabriel Garcia Marquez&apos;s magical realism, but this book was less strange that 100 Years of Solitude. <br/><br/>Two naive Americans—Richard and Sara Everton—move to the remote Mexican village of Ibarra to reopen a long-abandoned copper mine. They are not religious people, yet Sara seems to have a spiritual sensitivity and sight. The natives are depicted with respect for their cultu</span>
  <span id="freeText12362389803994062419" style="display:none">This book was sumptuous—the writing spare but rich with imagery and depth of scene, culture, and characters. I was reminded of Gabriel Garcia Marquez's magical realism, but this book was less strange that 100 Years of Solitude. <br /><br />Two naive Americans—Richard and Sara Everton—move to the remote Mexican village of Ibarra to reopen a long-abandoned copper mine. They are not religious people, yet Sara seems to have a spiritual sensitivity and sight. The natives are depicted with respect for their culturally unique combination of poor education, faith laced with spiritualism, and deep innate wisdom.<br /><br />The author also beautifully conveys the arid, sparse land that has its own power and magic to draw the Evertons in with mystery and promise. <br /><br />Some phrases/sentences I loved:<br />"...to weave chance and hope into a fabric that would clothe them as long as they lived."<br /><br />"Memories are like corks left out of bottles. They swell. They no longer fit." <br /><br />"In Ibarra, half a year is no more than a shard chipped from the rock face of eternity."<br /><br />The description of the mouse-infested hacienda after 50 years of neglect was marvelously written, as was the telling of the hair-raising taxi ride Sara took to find a doctor for Richard in a neighboring town. <br /><br />The Evertons and Mexican natives were mysteries to each other, but they developed a genuine and pure mutual affection.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12362389803994062419" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

