  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_986338692" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/986338692" />
    <a title="Phyllis Gauker" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/29431445-phyllis-gauker"><img alt="Phyllis Gauker" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1394275940p2/29431445.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/986338692?book_show_action=true">Jul 04, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Phyllis Gauker" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Phyllis Gauker" href="/user/show/29431445-phyllis-gauker">Phyllis Gauker</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer986338692" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer585695166504394586">This is truly a wonderful book if you have any interest in other cultures. The story is about an American couple who move, sight unseen (except in old photographs), from California to a tiny village 80 kilometers from the nearest big town in Mexico to attempt to revise a mine which had been started by his grandfather. I loved the intimacy of the couple, his tolerating her making up stories about the people from the few facts at hand, her refusal to deal with his doctor&apos;s prediction of only 6 mor</span>
  <span id="freeText585695166504394586" style="display:none">This is truly a wonderful book if you have any interest in other cultures. The story is about an American couple who move, sight unseen (except in old photographs), from California to a tiny village 80 kilometers from the nearest big town in Mexico to attempt to revise a mine which had been started by his grandfather. I loved the intimacy of the couple, his tolerating her making up stories about the people from the few facts at hand, her refusal to deal with his doctor's prediction of only 6 more years to live, and with her halting Spanish, determining (maybe?) the background of her Spanish teacher who was an 8 fingered, ancient nun. She constantly wants to understand the people, and this is her way of making it all fit: by fabricating stories. We, the readers, are privy to her thought process. We are also privy to the words of the locals who are trying to figure her out, knowing in some way, that the two cultures just do not match. They are agnostics amidst Roman Catholics. No one tries to convert them. They are accepted as being different. Having lived overseas in other Spanish speaking cultures, I enjoyed hearing the Spanish words and customs. I think I will send my copy to a retired Spanish teacher who lived in Mexico.</span>
  <a data-text-id="585695166504394586" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

